lines.text: INTRODUCTION I do not know how familiar some of you may be, either from your reading or from hearsay, with psychoanalysis.
lines.pos: nnp nnp vbp rb vb wrb jj dt in prp md vb , dt in prp$ vbg cc in nn , in nns .

lines.text: But, in keeping with the title of these lectures--_A General Introduction to Psychoanalysis_--I am obliged to proceed as though you knew nothing about this subject, and stood in need of preliminary instruction.
lines.pos: cc , in vbg in dt nn in dt nns cd nn jj nnp to nnp cd nnp vbp vbn to vb in in prp vbd nn in dt nn , cc vbd in vbn in jj nn .

lines.text: To be sure, this much I may presume that you do know, namely, that psychoanalysis is a method of treating nervous patients medically.
lines.pos: to vb jj , dt jj nnp md vb in prp vbp vb , rb , in nns vbz dt nn in vbg jj nns rb .

lines.text: And just at this point I can give you an example to illustrate how the procedure in this field is precisely the reverse of that which is the rule in medicine.
lines.pos: cc rb in dt nn nnp md vb prp dt nn to vb wrb dt nn in dt nn vbz rb dt nn in in wdt vbz dt nn in nn .

lines.text: Usually when we introduce a patient to a medical technique which is strange to him we minimize its difficulties and give him confident promises concerning the result of the treatment.
lines.pos: rb wrb prp vb dt nn to dt jj nn wdt vbz jj to prp prp vb prp$ nns cc vb prp jj vbz vbg dt nn in dt nn .

lines.text: When, however, we undertake psychoanalytic treatment with a neurotic patient we proceed differently.
lines.pos: wrb , rb , prp vb jj nn in dt jj nn prp vb rb .

lines.text: We hold before him the difficulties of the method, its length, the exertions and the sacrifices which it will cost him; and, as to the result, we tell him that we make no definite promises, that the result depends on his conduct, on his understanding, on his adaptability, on his perseverance.
lines.pos: prp vb in prp dt nns in dt nn , prp$ nn , dt nns cc dt nns wdt prp md nn prp ; cc , in to dt nn , prp vb prp in prp vb dt jj vbz , in dt nn vbz in prp$ nn , in prp$ vbg , in prp$ nn , in prp$ nn .

lines.text: We have, of course, excellent motives for conduct which seems so perverse, and into which you will perhaps gain insight at a later point in these lectures.
lines.pos: prp vbp , in nn , jj nns in nn wdt vbz rb jj , cc in wdt prp md rb nn nn in dt jj nn in dt nns .

lines.text: Do not be offended, therefore, if, for the present, I treat you as I treat these neurotic patients.
lines.pos: vbp rb vb vbn , rb , in , in dt jj , nnp vb prp in nnp vb dt jj nns .

lines.text: Frankly, I shall dissuade you from coming to hear me a second time.
lines.pos: rb , nnp md vb prp in vbg to vb prp dt nn nn .

lines.text: With this intention I shall show what imperfections are necessarily involved in the teaching of psychoanalysis and what difficulties stand in the way of gaining a personal judgment.
lines.pos: in dt nn nnp md nn wp nns vbp rb vbn in dt vbg in nns cc wp nns vb in dt nn in vbg dt jj nn .

lines.text: I shall show you how the whole trend of your previous training and all your accustomed mental habits must unavoidably have made you opponents of psychoanalysis, and how much you must overcome in yourselves in order to master this instinctive opposition.
lines.pos: nnp md nn prp wrb dt jj nn in prp$ jj vbg cc dt prp$ vbn jj nns md rb vbp vbn prp nns in nns , cc wrb jj prp md vb in prp in nn to nn dt jj nn .

lines.text: Of course I cannot predict how much psychoanalytic understanding you will gain from my lectures, but I can promise this, that by listening to them you will not learn how to undertake a psychoanalytic treatment or how to carry one to completion.
lines.pos: in nn nnp md rb vbp wrb jj jj vbg prp md nn in prp$ nns , cc nnp md nn dt , in in vbg to prp prp md rb vb wrb to vb dt jj nn cc wrb to vb cd to nn .

lines.text: Furthermore, should I find anyone among you who does not feel satisfied with a cursory acquaintance with psychoanalysis, but who would like to enter into a more enduring relationship with it, I shall not only dissuade him, but I shall actually warn him against it.
lines.pos: rb , md nnp vb nn in prp wp vbz rb vb vbn in dt jj nn in nns , cc wp md in to vb in dt jjr vbg nn in prp , nnp md rb rb vb prp , cc nnp md rb vb prp in prp .

lines.text: As things now stand, a person would, by such a choice of profession, ruin his every chance of success at a university, and if he goes out into the world as a practicing physician, he will find himself in a society which does not understand his aims, which regards him with suspicion and hostility, and which turns loose upon him all the malicious spirits which lurk within it.
lines.pos: in nns rb vb , dt nn md , in jj dt nn in nn , nn prp$ dt nn in nn in dt nn , cc in prp vbz in in dt nn in dt vbg nn , prp md vb prp in dt nn wdt vbz rb vb prp$ vbz , wdt vbz prp in nn cc nn , cc wdt vbz jj in prp dt dt jj nns wdt vb in prp .

lines.text: However, there are always enough individuals who are interested in anything which may be added to the sum total of knowledge, despite such inconveniences.
lines.pos: rb , ex vbp rb rb nns wp vbp jj in nn wdt md vb vbd to dt nn jj in nn , in jj nns .

lines.text: Should there be any of this type among you, and should they ignore my dissuasion and return to the next of these lectures, they will be welcome.
lines.pos: md ex vb dt in dt nn in prp , cc md prp vb prp$ nn cc nn to dt jj in dt nns , prp md vb jj .

lines.text: But all of you have the right to know what these difficulties of psychoanalysis are to which I have alluded.
lines.pos: cc dt in prp vbp dt nn to vb wp dt nns in nns vbp to wdt nnp vbp vbd .

lines.text: First of all, we encounter the difficulties inherent in the teaching and exposition of psychoanalysis.
lines.pos: nnp in dt , prp nn dt nns jj in dt vbg cc nn in nns .

lines.text: In your medical instruction you have been accustomed to visual demonstration.
lines.pos: in prp$ jj nn prp vbp vbn vbn to jj nn .

lines.text: You see the anatomical specimen, the precipitate in the chemical reaction, the contraction of the muscle as the result of the stimulation of its nerves.
lines.pos: prp vb dt jj nn , dt nn in dt jj nn , dt nn in dt nn in dt nn in dt nn in prp$ nns .

lines.text: Later the patient is presented to your senses; the symptoms of his malady, the products of the pathological processes, in many cases even the cause of the disease is shown in isolated state.
lines.pos: rb dt nn vbz vbn to prp$ nns ; dt nns in prp$ nn , dt nns in dt jj nns , in jj nns rb dt nn in dt nn vbz vbn in vbn nn .

lines.text: In the surgical department you are made to witness the steps by which one brings relief to the patient, and are permitted to attempt to practice them.
lines.pos: in dt jj nn prp vbp vbn to nn dt nns in wdt cd vbz nn to dt nn , cc vbp vbn to nn to nn prp .

lines.text: Even in psychiatry, the demonstration affords you, by the patient's changed facial play, his manner of speech and his behavior, a wealth of observations which leave far-reaching impressions.
lines.pos: rb in nn , dt nn vbz prp , in dt nns vbn jj vb , prp$ nn in nn cc prp$ nn , dt nn in nns wdt vb nn nns .

lines.text: Thus the medical teacher preponderantly plays the role of a guide and instructor who accompanies you through a museum in which you contract an immediate relationship to the exhibits, and in which you believe yourself to have been convinced through your own observation of the existence of the new things you see.
lines.pos: rb dt jj nn rb vbz dt nn in dt nn cc nn wp vbz prp in dt nn in wdt prp nn dt jj nn to dt nns , cc in wdt prp vbp prp to vbp vbn vbn in prp$ jj nn in dt nn in dt jj nns prp vb .

lines.text: Unfortunately, everything is different in psychoanalysis.
lines.pos: rb , nn vbz jj in nns .

lines.text: In psychoanalysis nothing occurs but the interchange of words between the patient and the physician.
lines.pos: in nns nn vbz cc dt nn in nns in dt nn cc dt nn .

lines.text: The patient talks, tells of his past experiences and present impressions, complains, confesses his wishes and emotions.
lines.pos: dt nn vbz , vbz in prp$ jj nns cc jj nns , vbz , vbz prp$ vbz cc nns .

lines.text: The physician listens, tries to direct the thought processes of the patient, reminds him of things, forces his attention into certain channels, gives him explanations and observes the reactions of understanding or denial which he calls forth in the patient.
lines.pos: dt nn vbz , vbz to jj dt nn vbz in dt nn , vbz prp in nns , nns prp$ nn in jj nns , vbz prp nns cc vbz dt nns in vbg cc jj wdt prp vbz rb in dt nn .

lines.text: The uneducated relatives of our patients--persons who are impressed only by the visible and tangible, preferably by such procedure as one sees in the moving picture theatres--never miss an opportunity of voicing their scepticism as to how one can "do anything for the malady through mere talk."
lines.pos: dt jj nns in prp$ nns cd nns wp vbp vbn rb in dt jj cc jj , rb in jj nn in cd vbz in dt vbg nn nns cd rb vb dt nn in vbg prp$ nn in to wrb cd md " vbp nn in dt nn in jj vb . "

lines.text: Such thinking, of course, is as shortsighted as it is inconsistent.
lines.pos: jj vbg , in nn , vbz in jj in prp vbz jj .

lines.text: For these are the very persons who know with such certainty that the patients "merely imagine" their symptoms.
lines.pos: in dt nn dt jj nns wp vb in jj nn in dt nns " rb vb " prp$ nns .

lines.text: Words were originally magic, and the word retains much of its old magical power even to-day.
lines.pos: nnps vbd rb nn , cc dt nn vbz jj in prp$ jj jj nn rb nn .

lines.text: With words one man can make another blessed, or drive him to despair; by words the teacher transfers his knowledge to the pupil; by words the speaker sweeps his audience with him and determines its judgments and decisions.
lines.pos: in nns cd nn md vb dt vbn , cc nn prp to nn ; in nns dt nn vbz prp$ nn to dt nn ; in nns dt nn vbz prp$ nn in prp cc vbz prp$ nns cc nns .

lines.text: Words call forth effects and are the universal means of influencing human beings.
lines.pos: nnps vb rb nns cc vbp dt jj vbz in vbg jj nns .

lines.text: Therefore let us not underestimate the use of words in psychotherapy, and let us be satisfied if we may be auditors of the words which are exchanged between the analyst and his patient.
lines.pos: rb vb prp rb vb dt nn in nns in nn , cc vb prp vb vbn in prp md vb nns in dt nns wdt vbp vbn in dt nn cc prp$ nn .

lines.text: But even that is impossible.
lines.pos: cc rb in vbz jj .

lines.text: The conversation of which the psychoanalytic treatment consists brooks no auditor, it cannot be demonstrated.
lines.pos: dt nn in wdt dt jj nn vbz nns dt nn , prp md rb vb vbn .

lines.text: One can, of course, present a neurasthenic or hysteric to the students in a psychiatric lecture.
lines.pos: cd md , in nn , jj dt nn cc nn to dt nns in dt jj nn .

lines.text: He tells of his complaints and symptoms, but of nothing else.
lines.pos: prp vbz in prp$ nns cc nns , cc in nn rb .

lines.text: The communications which are necessary for the analysis are made only under the conditions of a special affective relationship to the physician; the patient would become dumb as soon as he became aware of a single impartial witness.
lines.pos: dt nns wdt vbp jj in dt nns vbp vbn rb in dt nns in dt jj nn nn to dt nn ; dt nn md vb jj in rb in prp vbd jj in dt jj jj nn .

lines.text: For these communications concern the most intimate part of his psychic life, everything which as a socially independent person he must conceal from others; these communications deal with everything which, as a harmonious personality, he will not admit even to himself.
lines.pos: in dt nns nn dt jj jj nn in prp$ jj nn , nn wdt in dt rb jj nn prp md vb in nns ; dt nns jj in nn wdt , in dt jj nn , prp md rb vb rb to prp .

lines.text: You cannot, therefore, "listen in" on a psychoanalytic treatment.
lines.pos: prp md rb , rb , " vb in " in dt jj nn .

lines.text: You can only hear of it.
lines.pos: prp md rb vb in prp .

lines.text: You will get to know psychoanalysis, in the strictest sense of the word, only by hearsay.
lines.pos: prp md vb to vb nns , in dt jjs nn in dt nn , rb in nn .

lines.text: Such instruction even at second hand, will place you in quite an unusual position for forming a judgment.
lines.pos: jj nn rb in nn nn , md nn prp in rb dt jj nn in vbg dt nn .

lines.text: For it is obvious that everything depends on the faith you are able to put in the instructor.
lines.pos: in prp vbz jj in nn vbz in dt nn prp vbp jj to vb in dt nn .

lines.text: Imagine that you are not attending a psychiatric, but an historical lecture, and that the lecturer is telling you about the life and martial deeds of Alexander the Great.
lines.pos: vb in prp vbp rb vbg dt jj , cc dt jj nn , cc in dt nn vbz vbg prp in dt nn cc jj nns in nnp dt jj .

lines.text: What would be your reasons for believing in the authenticity of his statements?
lines.pos: wp md vb prp$ nns in vbg in dt nn in prp$ nns ?

lines.text: At first sight, the condition of affairs seems even more unfavorable than in the case of psychoanalysis, for the history professor was as little a participant in Alexander's campaigns as you were; the psychoanalyst at least tells you of things in connection with which he himself has played some role.
lines.pos: in nn nn , dt nn in nns vbz rb jjr jj in in dt nn in nns , in dt nn nn vbd in jj dt nn in nnps nns in prp vbd ; dt nn in jjs vbz prp in nns in nn in wdt prp prp vbz vbd dt nn .

lines.text: But then the question turns on this--what set of facts can the historian marshal in support of his position?
lines.pos: cc rb dt nn vbz in dt cd wp vbn in nns md dt nn jj in nn in prp$ nn ?

lines.text: He can refer you to the accounts of ancient authors, who were either contemporaries themselves, or who were at least closer to the events in question; that is, he will refer you to the books of Diodor, Plutarch, Arrian, etc.
lines.pos: prp md vb prp to dt nns in jj nns , wp vbd dt nns prp , cc wp vbd in jjs jjr to dt nns in nn ; in vbz , prp md vb prp to dt nns in nnp , nnp , nnp , nn .

lines.text: He can place before you pictures of the preserved coins and statues of the king and can pass down your rows a photograph of the Pompeiian mosaics of the battle of Issos.
lines.pos: prp md nn in prp vbz in dt vbn nns cc nns in dt nn cc md vb rb prp$ nns dt nn in dt nnp nns in dt nn in nnps .

lines.text: Yet, strictly speaking, all these documents prove only that previous generations already believed in Alexander's existence and in the reality of his deeds, and your criticism might begin anew at this point.
lines.pos: rb , rb vbg , dt dt nns vb rb in jj nns rb vbd in nnps nn cc in dt nn in prp$ nns , cc prp$ nn md vb rb in dt nn .

lines.text: You will then find that not everything recounted of Alexander is credible, or capable of proof in detail; yet even then I cannot believe that you will leave the lecture hall a disbeliever in the reality of Alexander the Great.
lines.pos: prp md rb vb in rb nn vbd in nnp vbz jj , cc jj in nn in nn ; rb rb rb nnp md rb vbp in prp md vb dt nn nn dt nn in dt nn in nnp dt jj .

lines.text: Your decision will be determined chiefly by two considerations; firstly, that the lecturer has no conceivable motive for presenting as truth something which he does not himself believe to be true, and secondly, that all available histories present the events in approximately the same manner.
lines.pos: prp$ nn md vb vbn rb in cd nns ; rb , in dt nn vbz dt jj nn in vbg in nn nn wdt prp vbz rb prp vbp to vb jj , cc rb , in dt jj nns jj dt nns in rb dt jj nn .

lines.text: If you then proceed to the verification of the older sources, you will consider the same data, the possible motives of the writers and the consistency of the various parts of the evidence.
lines.pos: in prp rb vb to dt nn in dt jjr nns , prp md vb dt jj nns , dt jj nns in dt nns cc dt nn in dt jj nns in dt nn .

lines.text: The result of the examination will surely be convincing in the case of Alexander.
lines.pos: dt nn in dt nn md rb vb jj in dt nn in nnp .

lines.text: It will probably turn out differently when applied to individuals like Moses and Nimrod.
lines.pos: prp md rb vb in rb wrb vbn to nns in nnps cc nnp .

lines.text: But what doubts you might raise against the credibility of the psychoanalytic reporter you will see plainly enough upon a later occasion.
lines.pos: cc wp nns prp md vb in dt nn in dt jj nn prp md vb rb rb in dt jj nn .

lines.text: At this point you have a right to raise the question, "If there is no such thing as objective verification of psychoanalysis, and no possibility of demonstrating it, how can one possibly learn psychoanalysis and convince himself of the truth of its claims?"
lines.pos: in dt nn prp vbp dt nn to vb dt nn , " in ex vbz dt jj nn in nn nn in nns , cc dt nn in vbg prp , wrb md cd rb vb nns cc vb prp in dt nn in prp$ nns ? "

lines.text: The fact is, the study is not easy and there are not many persons who have learned psychoanalysis thoroughly; but nevertheless, there is a feasible way.
lines.pos: dt nn vbz , dt nn vbz rb jj cc ex vbp rb jj nns wp vbp vbd nns rb ; cc rb , ex vbz dt jj nn .

lines.text: Psychoanalysis is learned, first of all, from a study of one's self, through the study of one's own personality.
lines.pos: nnps vbz vbd , nn in dt , in dt nn in nns nn , in dt nn in nns jj nn .

lines.text: This is not quite what is ordinarily called self-observation, but, at a pinch, one can sum it up thus.
lines.pos: dt nns rb rb wp vbz rb vbn nn , cc , in dt nn , cd md nn prp in rb .

lines.text: There is a whole series of very common and universally known psychic phenomena, which, after some instruction in the technique of psychoanalysis, one can make the subject matter of analysis in one's self.
lines.pos: ex vbz dt jj nn in rb jj cc rb vbn jj nns , wdt , in dt nn in dt nn in nns , cd md vb dt nn nn in nns in nns nn .

lines.text: By so doing one obtains the desired conviction of the reality of the occurrences which psychoanalysis describes and of the correctness of its fundamental conception.
lines.pos: in rb vbg cd nns dt vbn nn in dt nn in dt nns wdt nns vbz cc in dt nn in prp$ jj nn .

lines.text: To be sure, there are definite limits imposed on progress by this method.
lines.pos: to vb jj , ex vbp jj nns vbn in nn in dt nn .

lines.text: One gets much further if one allows himself to be analyzed by a competent analyst, observes the effect of the analysis on his own ego, and at the same time makes use of the opportunity to become familiar with the finer details of the technique of procedure.
lines.pos: cd vbz jj jj in cd vbz prp to vb vbn in dt jj nn , vbz dt nn in dt nns in prp$ jj nn , cc in dt jj nn vbz nn in dt nn to vb jj in dt jjr nns in dt nn in nn .

lines.text: This excellent method is, of course, only practicable for one person, never for an entire class.
lines.pos: dt jj nn vbz , in nn , rb jj in cd nn , rb in dt jj nn .

lines.text: There is a second difficulty in your relation to psychoanalysis for which I cannot hold the science itself responsible, but for which I must ask you to take the responsibility upon yourselves, ladies and gentlemen, at least in so far as you have hitherto pursued medical studies.
lines.pos: ex vbz dt nn nn in prp$ nn to nns in wdt nnp md rb vb dt nn prp jj , cc in wdt nnp md vb prp to vb dt nn in prp , nns cc nns , in jjs in rb rb in prp vbp rb vbn jj nns .

lines.text: Your previous training has given your mental activity a definite bent which leads you far away from psychoanalysis.
lines.pos: prp$ jj vbg vbz vbn prp$ jj nn dt jj vbd wdt vbz prp rb rb in nns .

lines.text: You have been trained to reduce the functions of an organism and its disorders anatomically, to explain them in terms of chemistry and physics and to conceive them biologically, but no portion of your interest has been directed to the psychic life, in which, after all, the activity of this wonderfully complex organism culminates.
lines.pos: prp vbp vbn vbn to vb dt nns in dt nn cc prp$ nns rb , to vb prp in nns in nn cc nn cc to vb prp rb , cc dt nn in prp$ nn vbz vbn vbn to dt jj nn , in wdt , in dt , dt nn in dt rb jj nn vbz .

lines.text: For this reason psychological thinking has remained strange to you and you have accustomed yourselves to regard it with suspicion, to deny it the character of the scientific, to leave it to the laymen, poets, natural philosophers and mystics.
lines.pos: in dt nn jj vbg vbz vbd jj to prp cc prp vbp vbn prp to nn prp in nn , to vb prp dt nn in dt jj , to vb prp to dt nns , nns , jj nns cc nns .

lines.text: I am not overlooking the excuse, whose existence one must admit, for this deficiency in your previous training.
lines.pos: nnp vbp rb vbg dt nn , wp$ nn cd md vb , in dt nn in prp$ jj vbg .

lines.text: There is no philosophical science of therapy which could be made practicable for your medical purpose.
lines.pos: ex vbz dt jj nn in nn wdt md vb vbn jj in prp$ jj nn .

lines.text: Within the field of medicine, psychiatry does, it is true, occupy itself with the description of the observed psychic disorders and with their grouping into clinical symptom-pictures; but in their better hours the psychiatrists themselves doubt whether their purely descriptive account deserves the name of a science.
lines.pos: in dt nn in nn , nn vbz , prp vbz jj , vb prp in dt nn in dt vbn jj nns cc in prp$ vbg in jj nns ; cc in prp$ jjr nns dt nns prp nn in prp$ rb jj nn vbz dt nn in dt nn .

lines.text: The symptoms which constitute these clinical pictures are known neither in their origin, in their mechanism, nor in their mutual relationship.
lines.pos: dt nns wdt vbp dt jj nns vbp vbn dt in prp$ nn , in prp$ nn , cc in prp$ jj nn .

lines.text: There are either no discoverable corresponding changes of the anatomical organ of the soul, or else the changes are of such a nature as to yield no enlightenment.
lines.pos: ex vbp dt dt nn jj nns in dt jj nn in dt nn , cc rb dt nns vbp in jj dt nn in to vb dt nn .

lines.text: Such psychic disturbances are open to therapeutic influence only when they can be identified as secondary phenomena of an otherwise organic affection.
lines.pos: jj jj nns vbp jj to jj nn rb wrb prp md vb vbn in jj nns in dt jj jj nn .

lines.text: Here is the gap which psychoanalysis aims to fill.
lines.pos: rb vbz dt nn wdt nns vbz to vb .

lines.text: It prepares to give psychiatry the omitted psychological foundation, it hopes to reveal the common basis from which, as a starting point, constant correlation of bodily and psychic disturbances becomes comprehensible.
lines.pos: prp vbz to vb nn dt vbn jj nn , prp vbz to vb dt jj nns in wdt , in dt vbg nn , jj nn in rb cc jj nns vbz nn .

lines.text: To this end, it must divorce itself from every anatomical, chemical or physiological supposition which is alien to it.
lines.pos: to dt nn , prp md nn prp in dt jj , jj cc jj nn wdt vbz jj to prp .

lines.text: It must work throughout with purely psychological therapeutic concepts, and just for that reason I fear that it will at first seem strange to you.
lines.pos: prp md nn in in rb jj jj nns , cc rb in in nn nnp nn in prp md in nn vb jj to prp .

lines.text: I will not make you, your previous training, or your mental bias share the guilt of the next difficulty.
lines.pos: nnp md rb vb prp , prp$ jj vbg , cc prp$ jj nns nn dt nn in dt jj nn .

lines.text: With two of its assertions, psychoanalysis offends the whole world and draws aversion upon itself.
lines.pos: in cd in prp$ nns , nns vbz dt jj nn cc vbz nn in prp .

lines.text: One of these assertions offends an intellectual prejudice, the other an aesthetic-moral one.
lines.pos: cd in dt nns vbz dt jj nn , dt jj dt jj cd .

lines.text: Let us not think too lightly of these prejudices; they are powerful things, remnants of useful, even necessary, developments of mankind.
lines.pos: vb prp rb vbp rb rb in dt nns ; prp vbp jj nns , nns in jj , rb jj , nns in nn .

lines.text: They are retained through powerful affects, and the battle against them is a hard one.
lines.pos: prp vbp vbn in jj vbz , cc dt nn in prp vbz dt jj cd .

lines.text: The first of these displeasing assertions of psychoanalysis is this, that the psychic processes are in themselves unconscious, and that those which are conscious are merely isolated acts and parts of the total psychic life.
lines.pos: dt nn in dt nn nns in nns vbz dt , in dt jj nns vbp in prp jj , cc in dt wdt vbp jj vbp rb vbn nns cc nns in dt jj jj nn .

lines.text: Recollect that we are, on the contrary, accustomed to identify the psychic with the conscious.
lines.pos: vbp in prp vbp , in dt jj , vbn to vb dt jj in dt jj .

lines.text: Consciousness actually means for us the distinguishing characteristic of the psychic life, and psychology is the science of the content of consciousness.
lines.pos: nnp rb vbz in prp dt vbg jj in dt jj nn , cc nn vbz dt nn in dt nn in nn .

lines.text: Indeed, so obvious does this identification seem to us that we consider its slightest contradiction obvious nonsense, and yet psychoanalysis cannot avoid raising this contradiction; it cannot accept the identity of the conscious with the psychic.
lines.pos: rb , rb jj vbz dt nn vb to prp in prp vb prp$ jjs nn jj nn , cc rb nns md rb vb vbg dt nn ; prp md rb vb dt nn in dt jj in dt jj .

lines.text: Its definition of the psychic affirms that they are processes of the nature of feeling, thinking, willing; and it must assert that there is such a thing as unconscious thinking and unconscious willing.
lines.pos: prp$ nn in dt jj vbz in prp vbp nns in dt nn in vbg , vbg , jj ; cc prp md vb in ex vbz jj dt nn in jj vbg cc jj jj .

lines.text: But with this assertion psychoanalysis has alienated, to start with, the sympathy of all friends of sober science, and has laid itself open to the suspicion of being a fantastic mystery study which would build in darkness and fish in murky waters.
lines.pos: cc in dt nn nns vbz vbn , to vb in , dt nn in dt nns in jj nn , cc vbz vbn prp jj to dt nn in vbg dt jj nn nn wdt md vb in nn cc nn in jj nns .

lines.text: You, however, ladies and gentlemen, naturally cannot as yet understand what justification I have for stigmatizing as a prejudice so abstract a phrase as this one, that "the psychic is consciousness."
lines.pos: prp , rb , nns cc nns , rb md rb in rb vb wp nn nnp vbp in nn in dt nn rb jj dt nn in dt cd , in " dt jj vbz nn . "

lines.text: You cannot know what evaluation can have led to the denial of the unconscious, if such a thing really exists, and what advantage may have resulted from this denial.
lines.pos: prp md rb vb wp nn md vbp vbn to dt jj in dt jj , in jj dt nn rb vbz , cc wp nn md vbp vbd in dt jj .

lines.text: A second, far more important and more extensive consideration, equally disregarded by the layman, is the following: A wish-fulfillment certainly must bring pleasure--but to whom?

lines.text: Instead of further explanations I shall give you a well-known fairy tale, in which you will again find the relationships I have mentioned.

lines.text: It will not be difficult now to come to a better understanding of the anxiety-dream.

lines.text: We shall make one more observation, then we shall come to a conclusion to which many things lead.

lines.text: The observation is that the anxiety dreams often have a content which is entirely free from distortion and in which the censorship is, so to speak, eluded.

lines.text: The anxiety dream is ofttimes an undisguised wish-fulfillment, not, to be sure, of an accepted, but of a discarded wish.

lines.text: The anxiety development has stepped into the place of the censorship.

lines.text: While one may assert of the infantile dream that it is the obvious fulfillment of a wish that has gained admittance, and of the distorted dream that it is the disguised fulfillment of a suppressed wish, he must say of the anxiety dream that the only suitable formula is this, that it is the obvious fulfillment of a suppressed wish.

lines.text: Anxiety is the mark which shows that the suppressed wish showed itself stronger than the censorship, that it put through its wish-fulfillment despite the censorship, or was about to put it through.

lines.text: We understand that what is wish-fulfillment for the suppressed wish is for us, who are on the side of the dream-censor, only a painful sensation and a cause for antagonism.

lines.text: The anxiety which occurs in dreams is, if you wish, anxiety because of the strength of these otherwise suppressed wishes.

lines.text: What holds true for the undistorted anxiety dream we may assume to be true also of those dreams which have undergone partial distortion, and of the other dreams of aversion whose painful impressions very probably denote approximations of anxiety.

lines.text: This so-called compulsion neurosis is not so popular as the widely known hysteria; it is, if I may use the expression, not so noisily ostentatious, behaves more as a private concern of the patient, renounces bodily manifestations almost entirely and creates all its symptoms psychologically.

lines.text: Of these the compulsion neurosis, which does not take that mysterious leap from the psychic to the physical, has through psychoanalytic research become more intimately comprehensible and transparent to us than hysteria, and we have come to understand that it reveals far more vividly certain extreme characteristics of the neuroses.

lines.text: The chief manifestations of compulsion neurosis are these: the patient is occupied by thoughts that in reality do not interest him, is moved by impulses that appear alien to him, and is impelled to actions which, to be sure, afford him no pleasure, but the performance of which he cannot possibly resist.

lines.text: To bring this home to us more vividly, let us assume that every psychological process--with one exception, which I will go into later--first exists in an unconscious state or phase and only goes over from this into a conscious phase, much as a photographic picture is first a negative and then becomes a picture by being printed.

lines.text: We find it advantageous to express ourselves as follows: Any particular process belongs in the first place to the psychological system of the unconscious; from this system it can under certain conditions go over into the system of the conscious.

lines.text: We therefore justifiably call this second room the system of the _fore-conscious_.

lines.text: This ill-assorted array fairly clamors for orderly classification if it is not to bewilder our senses.
lines.pos: dt vbn nn rb nns in rb nn in prp vbz rb to nn prp$ nns .

lines.text: We first divide them, on the one hand, into those whose sexual object has changed, as is the case with homosexualists, and, on the other, those whose sexual aim has changed.

lines.text: Those of the first group have dispensed with the mutual union of the genital organs, and have, as one of the partners of the act, replaced the genitals by another organ or part of the body; they have thus overcome both the short-comings of organic structure and the usual disgust involved.

lines.text: By means of these individuals we realize that the functions of excretion, which in the education of the child are hushed away as indecent, still remain capable of drawing complete sexual interest on themselves.

lines.text: Here also belong the enigmatic sadists, whose affectionate strivings know no other goal than to cause their object pain and agony, varying all the way from humiliating suggestions to the harshest physical ill-treatment.

lines.text: It is, in short, our unavoidable task to account theoretically for all the potentialities of the perversions we have gone over and to explain their relation to the so-called normal sexuality.

lines.text: Self-denial gives rise to conflict, for libido deprived of its gratification is forced to seek other means and ends.

lines.text: They are, in the widest sense, the non-sexual impulses.

lines.text: We call them comprehensively the "ego impulses"; psychoanalysis of transference neuroses does not grant us ready access to their further investigation, but we learn to know them, in a measure, through the resistance they offer to analysis.

lines.text: The pathological struggle is waged between ego-impulses and sexual impulses.

lines.text: In a series of cases it appears as though conflict could exist between various purely sexual desires; but that is really the same thing, for of the two sexual desires involved in the conflict, one is always considerate of the ego, while the other demands that the ego be denied, and so it remains a conflict between the ego and sexuality.

lines.text: Only it has been destined to deal primarily with sexual impulses, because transference neuroses have furnished the readiest access to their investigation, and because it had become obligatory to study what others had neglected.

lines.text: The very distinction of the ego from sexuality has shown most clearly that the ego-impulses also pass through a significant development, which is by no means entirely independent of the development of the libido, nor does it fail to exert a reaction upon it.

lines.text: We do not dream of asserting that the libidinous interests of a person are from the outset opposed to the interests of self-preservation; in every stage, rather, the ego will strive to remain in harmony with its sexual organization at that time, and accommodate itself thereto.

lines.text: To show you the influence of ego development in the formation of a conflict, and so to give an illustration of the causation of neuroses, I should like to cite an example which, although it is entirely imaginary, is not far removed from probability in any respect.

lines.text: To appreciate the full significance of the aforementioned difference between the two groups of instincts, we must digress considerably and introduce a consideration which we must needs call _economic_.

lines.text: We ask ourselves whether a fundamental purpose is recognizable in the workings of our psychological apparatus, and answer immediately that this purpose is the pursuit of pleasurable excitement.

lines.text: It seems as if our entire psychological activity were directed toward gaining pleasurable stimulation, toward avoiding painful ones; that it is regulated automatically by the _principle of pleasure_.

lines.text: Now we should like to know, above all, what conditions cause the creation of pleasure and pain, but here we fall short.

lines.text: It thus appears that we can describe the tasks and performances of the psychic apparatus in different and more generalized terms than by the emphasis of the pursuit of pleasure.

lines.text: The sexual instincts obviously show their aim of pleasurable excitement from the beginning to the end of their development; they retain this original function without much change.

lines.text: The ego instincts strive at first for the same thing.

lines.text: The task of avoiding pain becomes an objective almost comparable to the gain of pleasure; the ego learns that its direct gratification is unavoidably withheld, the gain of pleasurable excitement postponed, that always a certain amount of pain must be borne and certain sources of pleasure entirely relinquished.
lines.pos: dt nn in vbg nn vbz dt nn rb jj to dt nn in nn ; dt nn vbz in prp$ jj nn vbz rb vbn , dt nn in jj nn vbn , in rb dt jj nn in nn md vb vbn cc jj nns in nn rb vbd .

lines.text: TWENTY-THIRD LECTURE GENERAL THEORY OF THE NEUROSES _The Development of the Symptoms_ In the layman's eyes the symptom shows the nature of the disease, and cure means removal of symptoms.
lines.pos: nnp nnp jj nnp in dt nnps nn nnp in dt nnp in dt nns nns dt nn vbz dt nn in dt nn , cc nn vbz jj in nns .

lines.text: The physician, however, finds it important to distinguish the symptoms from the disease and recognizes that doing away with the symptoms is not necessarily curing the disease.
lines.pos: dt nn , rb , vbz prp jj to vb dt nns in dt nn cc vbz in vbg rb in dt nns vbz rb rb vbg dt nn .

lines.text: Of course, the only tangible thing left over after the removal of the symptoms is the capacity to build new symptoms.
lines.pos: in nn , dt rb jj nn vbn in in dt jj in dt nns vbz dt nn to vb jj nns .

lines.text: Accordingly, for the time being, let us accept the layman's viewpoint and consider the understanding of the symptoms as equivalent to the understanding of the sickness.

lines.text: The symptoms,--of course, we are dealing here with psychic (or psychogenic) symptoms, and psychic illness--are acts which are detrimental to life as a whole, or which are at least useless; frequently they are obnoxious to the individual who performs them and are accompanied by distaste and suffering.
lines.pos: dt nns , cd in nn , prp vbp vbg rb in jj ( cc nn ) nns , cc jj nn cd vbp nns wdt vbp jj to nn in dt jj , cc wdt vbp in jjs jj ; rb prp vbp jj to dt jj wp vbz prp cc vbp vbn in nn cc vbg .

lines.text: The principal injury lies in the psychic exertion which they cost, and in the further exertion needed to combat them.

lines.text: The price these efforts exact may, when there is an extensive development of the symptoms, bring about an extraordinary impoverishment of the personality of the patient with respect to his available psychic energy, and consequently cripple him in all the important tasks of life.

lines.text: Since such an outcome is dependent on the amount of energy so utilized, you will readily understand that "being sick" is essentially a practical concept.

lines.text: But if you take a theoretical standpoint and disregard these quantitative relations, you can readily say that we are all sick, or rather neurotic, since the conditions favorable to the development of symptoms are demonstrable also among normal persons.

lines.text: As to the neurotic symptoms, we already know that they are the result of a conflict aroused by a new form of gratifying the libido.

lines.text: The two forces that have contended against each other meet once more in the symptom; they become reconciled through the compromise of a symptom development.

lines.text: That is why the symptom is capable of such resistance; it is sustained from both sides.

lines.text: We also know that one of the two partners to the conflict is the unsatisfied libido, frustrated by reality, which must now seek other means for its satisfaction.

lines.text: If reality remains inflexible even where the libido is prepared to take another object in place of the one denied it, the libido will then finally be compelled to resort to regression and to seek gratification in one of the earlier stages in its organizations already out-lived, or by means of one of the objects given up in the past.

lines.text: Along the path of regression the libido is enticed by fixations which it has left behind at these stages in its development.

lines.text: Here the development toward perversion branches off sharply from that of the neuroses.

lines.text: The ego, however, controls not alone consciousness, but also the approaches to motor innervation, and hence the realization of psychic impulses.

lines.text: If the ego then does not approve this regression, the conflict takes place.

lines.text: The libido is locked out, as it were, and must seek refuge in some place where it can find an outlet for its fund of energy, in accordance with the controlling demands for pleasurable gratification.

lines.text: It must withdraw from the ego.

lines.text: Such an evasion is offered by the fixations established in the course of its evolution and now traversed regressively, against which the ego had, at the time, protected itself by suppressions.

lines.text: The libido, streaming back, occupies these suppressed positions and thus withdraws from before the ego and its laws.

lines.text: At the same time, however, it throws off all the influences acquired under its tutelage.

lines.text: The libido could be guided so long as there was a possibility of its being satisfied; under the double pressure of external and internal denial it becomes unruly and harks back to former and more happy times.

lines.text: Such is its character, fundamentally unchangeable.
lines.pos: jj vbz prp$ nn , rb nn .

lines.text: The ideas which the libido now takes over in order to hold its energy belong to the system of the unconscious, and are therefore subject to its peculiar processes, especially elaboration and displacement.

lines.text: Conditions are set up here which are entirely comparable to those of dream formation.
lines.pos: nnps vbp vbn in rb wdt vbp rb jj to dt in nn nn .

lines.text: Just as the latent dream, the fulfillment of a wish-phantasy, is first built up in the unconsciousness, but must then pass through conscious processes before, censored and approved, it can enter into the compromise construction of the manifest dream, so the ideas representing the libido in the unconscious must still contend against the power of the fore-conscious ego.

lines.text: The opposition that has arisen against it in the ego follows it down by a "counter-siege" and forces it to choose such an expression as will serve at the same time to express itself.

lines.text: Thus, then, the symptom comes into being as a much distorted offshoot from the unconscious libidinous wish-fulfillment, an artificially selected ambiguity--with two entirely contradictory meanings.

lines.text: In this last point alone do we realize a difference between dream and symptom development, for the only fore-conscious purpose in dream formation is the maintenance of sleep, the exclusion from consciousness of anything which may disturb sleep; but it does not necessarily oppose the unconscious wish impulse with an insistent "No."

lines.text: Quite the contrary; the purpose of the dream may be more tolerant, because the situation of the sleeper is a less dangerous one.

lines.text: The exit to reality is closed only through the condition of sleep.
lines.pos: dt nn to nn vbz vbd rb in dt nn in vb .

lines.text: You see, this evasion which the libido finds under the conditions of the conflict is possible only by virtue of the existing fixations.

lines.text: When these fixations are taken in hand by the regression, the suppression is side-tracked and the libido, which must maintain itself under the conditions of the compromise, is led off or gratified.

lines.text: By means of such a detour by way of the unconscious and the old fixations, the libido has at last succeeded in breaking its way through to some sort of gratification, however extraordinarily limited this may seem and however unrecognizable any longer as a genuine satisfaction.

lines.text: Now allow me to add two further remarks concerning this final result.

lines.text: In the first place, I should like you to take note of the intimate connection between the libido and the unconscious on the one hand, and on the other of the ego, consciousness, and reality.

lines.text: I should like you to bear continually in mind that everything I have said here, and all that will follow, pertains only to the symptom development of hysterical neurosis.

lines.text: The significance of this period of childhood is a double one; on the one hand, the instinctive tendencies which were congenital in the child first showed themselves at this time; secondly, at the same time, environmental influences and chance experiences were first awakening his other instincts.

lines.text: I believe our right to establish this bipartite division cannot be questioned.

lines.text: The assertion that the innate disposition plays a part is hardly open to criticism, but analytic experience actually makes it necessary for us to assume that purely accidental experiences of childhood are capable of leaving fixations of the libido.

lines.text: And is it conceivable that the inheritance of such acquired characters comes to a standstill in the very generation that we have under observation?

lines.text: If the infantile experiences, revealed by analysis, were in every case real, we should have the feeling of walking on sure ground; if they were regularly falsified, disclosed themselves as inventions or phantasies of the patients, we should have to leave this uncertain ground and find a surer footing elsewhere.

lines.text: In the first place we find a general condition of anxiety, a condition of free-floating fear as it were, which is ready to attach itself to any appropriate idea, to influence judgment, to give rise to expectations, in fact to seize any opportunity to make itself felt.

lines.text: A second form of fear in contrast to the one we have just described is psychologically more circumscribed and bound up with certain objects or situations.

lines.text: The second group consists of cases which still bear a relation to danger, but this is of a kind which we are disposed to belittle rather than to overestimate.

lines.text: The two forms of fear that have been described, free-floating fear and the fear which is bound up with phobias, are independent of one another.

lines.text: The strongest condition of general anxiety need not manifest itself in phobias; and persons whose entire life is hemmed in by agoraphobia can be entirely free of pessimistic expectant fear.

lines.text: Some phobias, such as the fear of squares or of trains, are acquired only in later life, while others, the fear of darkness, storms and animals, exist from the very beginning.

lines.text: I must add that we group all these phobias under _anxiety hysteria_, and therefore regard it as a condition closely related to the well-known conversion hysteria.

lines.text: TWENTY-EIGHTH LECTURE GENERAL THEORY OF THE NEUROSES _Analytical Therapy_ You know our subject for today.

lines.text: For years I practised hypnotic treatment, at first by means of prohibitory suggestions alone, and later by this method in combination with investigation of the patient after the manner of Breuer.

lines.text: Now let us add a few further considerations.

lines.text: The practice of hypnotic therapy demands only a slight amount of work of the patient as well as of the physician.

lines.text: But it is contrary to our dynamic conceptions that we should be able to move a great weight by an inconsiderable force, by attacking it directly and without the aid of appropriate preparations.

lines.text: In the light of the knowledge we have gained from psychoanalysis we can describe the difference between hypnotic and psychoanalytic suggestion as follows: Hypnotic therapy seeks to hide something in psychic life, and to gloss it over; analytic therapy seeks to lay it bare and to remove it.
lines.pos: in dt nn in dt nn prp vbp vbd in nns prp md vb dt nn in jj cc jj nn in vbz : jj nn vbz to vb nn in jj nn , cc to vb prp in ; jj nn vbz to vbd prp jj cc to vb prp .

lines.text: The first method works cosmetically, the other surgically.
lines.pos: dt nn nn vbz rb , dt jj rb .

lines.text: The first uses suggestion in order to prevent the appearance of the symptoms, it strengthens suppression, but leaves unchanged all other processes that have led to symptom development.
lines.pos: dt nn vbz nn in nn to vb dt nn in dt nns , prp vbz nn , cc vbz jj dt jj nns in vbp vbn to nn nn .

lines.text: Analytic therapy attacks the illness closer to its sources, namely in the conflicts out of which the symptoms have emerged, it makes use of suggestion to change the solution of these conflicts.
lines.pos: jj nn vbz dt nn jjr to prp$ nns , rb in dt nns in in wdt dt nns vbp vbd , prp vbz nn in nn to nn dt nn in dt nns .

lines.text: Hypnotic therapy leaves the patient inactive and unchanged, and therefore without resistance to every new occasion for disease.
lines.pos: jj nn vbz dt nn jj cc jj , cc rb in nn to dt jj nn in nn .

lines.text: Analytic treatment places upon the physician, as well as upon the patient, a difficult responsibility; the inner resistance of the patient must be abolished.
lines.pos: jj nn vbz in dt nn , in rb in in dt nn , dt jj nn ; dt jj nn in dt nn md vb vbn .

lines.text: The psychic life of the patient is permanently changed by overcoming these resistances, it is lifted upon a higher plane of development and remains protected against new possibilities of disease.

lines.text: The work of overcoming resistance is the fundamental task of the analytic cure.
lines.pos: dt nn in vbg nn vbz dt jj nn in dt jj nn .

lines.text: The patient, however, must take it on himself to accomplish this, while the physician, with the aid of suggestion, makes it possible for him to do so.

lines.text: The suggestion works in the nature of an _education_.

lines.text: We are therefore justified in saying that analytic treatment is a sort of _after-education_.
lines.pos: prp vbp rb vbn in vbg in jj nn vbz dt nn in nn .

lines.text: I hope I have made it clear to you wherein our technique of using suggestion differs therapeutically from the only use possible in hypnotic therapy.
lines.pos: nnp nn nnp vbp vbn prp jj to prp wrb prp$ nn in vbg nn vbz rb in dt rb nn jj in jj nn .

lines.text: With your knowledge of the relation between suggestion and transference you will readily understand the capriciousness of hypnotic therapy which attracted our attention, and you will see why, on the other hand, analytic suggestion can be relied upon to its limits.
lines.pos: in prp$ nn in dt nn in nn cc nn prp md rb vb dt nn in jj nn wdt vbn prp$ nn , cc prp md vb wrb , in dt jj nn , jj nn md vb vbn in to prp$ nns .

lines.text: In hypnosis we depend on the condition of the patient's capacity for transference, yet we are unable to exert any influence on this capacity.

lines.text: The transference of the subject may be negative, or, as is most frequent, ambivalent; the patient may have protected himself against suggestion by very special adjustments, yet we are unable to learn anything concerning them.

lines.text: In psychoanalysis we work with the transference itself, we do away with the forces opposing it, prepare the instrument with which we are to work.

lines.text: So it becomes possible to derive entirely new uses from the power of suggestion; we are able to control it, the patient does not work himself into any state of mind he pleases, but in so far as we are able to influence him at all, we can guide the suggestion.
lines.pos: rb prp vbz jj to vbp rb jj vbz in dt nn in nn ; prp vbp jj to nn prp , dt nn vbz rb nn prp in dt nn in nn prp vbz , cc in rb rb in prp vbp jj to nn prp in dt , prp md nn dt nn .

lines.text: Now you will say, regardless of whether we call the driving force of our analysis transference or suggestion, there is still the danger that through our influence on the patient the objective certainty of our discoveries becomes doubtful.

lines.text: That which becomes a benefit to therapy works harm to the investigation.

lines.text: This objection is most often raised against psychoanalysis, and it must be admitted that even if it does not hit the mark, it cannot be waved aside as stupid.

lines.text: But if it were justified, psychoanalysis would be nothing more than an extraordinarily well disguised and especially workable kind of treatment by suggestion, and we may lay little weight upon all its assertions concerning the influences of life, psychic dynamics, and the unconscious.

lines.text: This is in fact the opinion held by our opponents; we are supposed especially to have "balked into" the patients everything that supports the importance of sexual experiences, and often the experiences themselves, after the combinations themselves have grown up in our degenerate imaginations.

lines.text: We can refute these attacks most easily by calling on the evidence of experience rather than by resorting to theory.

lines.text: There is no difficulty, of course, in making the patient a disciple of any one theory, and thus causing him to share the possible error of the physician.

lines.text: With respect to this he behaves just like any other person, like a student, but he has influenced only his intelligence, not his disease.

lines.text: The solving of his conflicts and the overcoming of his resistances succeeds only if we have aroused in him representations of such expectations as can agree with reality.

lines.text: What was inapplicable in the assumptions of the physician falls away during the course of the analysis; it must be withdrawn and replaced by something more nearly correct.

lines.text: By employing a careful technique we seek to prevent the occurrence of temporary results arising out of suggestion, yet there is no harm if such temporary results occur, for we are never satisfied with early successes.

lines.text: We do not consider the analysis finished until all the obscurities of the case are cleared up, all amnestic gaps filled out and the occasions which originally called out the suppressions discovered.
lines.pos: prp vbp rb vb dt nns vbd in dt dt nns in dt nn vbp vbn in , dt nn nns vbn in cc dt nns wdt rb vbn in dt nns vbn .

lines.text: We see in results that are achieved too quickly a hindrance rather than a furtherance of analytic work and repeatedly we undo these results again by purposely breaking up the transference upon which they rest.
lines.pos: prp vb in nns in vbp vbn rb rb dt nn rb in dt nn in jj nn cc rb prp vb dt nns rb in rb vbg in dt nn in wdt prp nn .

lines.text: Fundamentally it is this feature which distinguishes analytical treatment from the purely suggestive technique and frees analytic results from the suspicion of having been suggested.
lines.pos: rb prp vbz dt nn wdt vbz jj nn in dt rb jj nn cc vbz jj nns in dt nn in vbg vbn vbd .

lines.text: Under every other suggestive treatment the transference itself is most carefully upheld and the influence left unquestioned; in analytic treatment, however, the transference becomes the subject of treatment and is subject to criticism in whatever form it may appear.

lines.text: At the end of an analytic cure the transference itself must be abolished; therefore the effect of the treatment, whether positive or negative, must be founded not upon suggestion but upon the overcoming of inner resistances, upon the inner change achieved in the patient, which the aid of suggestion has made possible.

lines.text: Furthermore, let me call your attention to the fact that a large number of results of analysis, otherwise perhaps subject to the suspicion that they are products of suggestion, can be confirmed from other unquestionable sources.
